                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1077">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">894.00/912: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-06-24T19:00:00+09:00"
                            >June 24, 1940—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 24—11:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>489. Our 486, June 23, 6 p.m.<note n="20" xml:id="d1077fn20">Not printed.</note>
                    Today Prince Konoye resigned as President of the Privy Council. There are rumors
                    to the effect that the resignation is preliminary to the formation of a new
                    Konoye Cabinet, and that alternatively or concurrently he will assume leadership
                    of the new Single Party Movement.</p>
                <pb facs="0971" n="963" xml:id="pg_963"/>
                <p>Mr. Yoshimichi Hara, formerly Vice-President of the Privy Council, replaces
                    Prince Konoye as President. His appointment is without special significance.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
